# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: waveform-audio
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] The **Nyquist–Shannon sampling theorem** is a theorem in the field of signal processing which serves as a fundamental bridge between continuous-time signals and discrete-time signals.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] Strictly speaking, the theorem only applies to a class of mathematical functions having a Fourier transform that is zero outside of a finite region of frequencies.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] Intuitively we expect that when one reduces a continuous function to a discrete sequence and interpolates back to a continuous function, the fidelity of the result depends on the density (or sample rate) of the original samples.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] The sampling theorem introduces the concept of a sample rate that is sufficient for perfect fidelity for the class of functions that are band-limited to a given bandwidth, such that no actual information is lost in the sampling process.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] It expresses the sufficient sample rate in terms of the bandwidth for the class of functions.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] The theorem also leads to a formula for perfectly reconstructing the original continuous-time function from the samples.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] Perfect reconstruction may still be possible when the sample-rate criterion is not satisfied, provided other constraints on the signal are known (see § Sampling of non-baseband signals below and compressed sensing).
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] In some cases (when the sample-rate criterion is not satisfied), utilizing additional constraints allows for approximate reconstructions.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] The fidelity of these reconstructions can be verified and quantified utilizing Bochner's theorem.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] An important consequence of the sampling theorem is the concept of Nyquist frequency, which holds that in order to reconstruct a bandlimited signal free of aliasing, the sampling rate must be at least twice the signal's bandwidth.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] The name *Nyquist–Shannon sampling theorem* honours Harry Nyquist and Claude Shannon, but the theorem was also previously discovered by E.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] Whittaker (published in 1915), and Shannon cited Whittaker's paper in his work.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] The theorem is thus also known by the names *Whittaker–Shannon sampling theorem*, *Whittaker–Shannon*, and *Whittaker–Nyquist–Shannon*, and may also be referred to as the *cardinal theorem of interpolation*.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] Sampling is a process of converting a signal (for example, a function of continuous time or space) into a sequence of values (a function of discrete time or space).
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] A sufficient sample-rate is therefore anything larger than $2B$ samples per second.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] Equivalently, for a given sample rate $f_{s}$ , perfect reconstruction is guaranteed possible for a bandlimit $B<f_{s}/2$ .
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] When the bandlimit is too high (or there is no bandlimit), the reconstruction exhibits imperfections known as aliasing.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] Modern statements of the theorem are sometimes careful to explicitly state that $x(t)$ must contain no sinusoidal component at exactly frequency $B,$ or that B must be strictly less than one half the sample rate.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] The threshold $2B$ is called the Nyquist rate and is an attribute of the continuous-time input $x(t)$ to be sampled.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] The sample rate must exceed the Nyquist rate for the samples to suffice to represent $x(t).$ The threshold $f_{s}/2$ is called the Nyquist frequency and is an attribute of the sampling equipment.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] All meaningful frequency components of the properly sampled $x(t)$ exist below the Nyquist frequency.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] The condition described by these inequalities is called the *Nyquist criterion*, or sometimes the *Raabe condition*.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] The theorem is also applicable to functions of other domains, such as space, in the case of a digitized image.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] The symbol $T\triangleq 1/f_{s}$ is customarily used to represent the interval between adjacent samples and is called the *sample period* or *sampling interval*.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] A mathematically ideal way to interpolate the sequence involves the use of sinc functions.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] Each sample in the sequence is replaced by a sinc function, centered on the time axis at the original location of the sample $nT,$ with the amplitude of the sinc function scaled to the sample value, $x(nT).$ Subsequently, the sinc functions are summed into a continuous function.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] A mathematically equivalent method uses the Dirac comb and proceeds by convolving one sinc function with a series of Dirac delta pulses, weighted by the sample values.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] Neither method is numerically practical.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] Instead, some type of approximation of the sinc functions, finite in length, is used.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] The imperfections attributable to the approximation are known as *interpolation error*.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] Practical digital-to-analog converters produce neither scaled and delayed sinc functions, nor ideal Dirac pulses.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] Instead they produce a piecewise-constant sequence of scaled and delayed rectangular pulses (the zero-order hold), usually followed by a lowpass filter (called an "anti-imaging filter") to remove spurious high-frequency replicas (images) of the original baseband signal.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] which is a periodic function and its equivalent representation as a Fourier series, whose coefficients are $x[n]$ .
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] This function is also known as the discrete-time Fourier transform (DTFT) of the sample sequence.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] As depicted, copies of $X(f)$ are shifted by multiples of the sampling rate $f_{s}=1/T$ and combined by addition.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] For a band-limited function $(X(f)=0,{\text{ for all }}|f|\geq B)$ and sufficiently large $f_{s},$ it is possible for the copies to remain distinct from each other.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] But if the Nyquist criterion is not satisfied, adjacent copies overlap, and it is not possible in general to discern an unambiguous $X(f).$ Any frequency component above $f_{s}/2$ is indistinguishable from a lower-frequency component, called an *alias*, associated with one of the copies.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] In such cases, the customary interpolation techniques produce the alias, rather than the original component.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] When the sample-rate is pre-determined by other considerations (such as an industry standard), $x(t)$ is usually filtered to reduce its high frequencies to acceptable levels before it is sampled.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] The type of filter required is a lowpass filter, and in this application it is called an anti-aliasing filter.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] The sampling theorem is proved since $X(f)$ uniquely determines $x(t)$ .
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] All that remains is to derive the formula for reconstruction. $H(f)$ need not be precisely defined in the region $[B,\ f_{s}-B]$ because $X_{1/T}(f)$ is zero in that region.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] However, the worst case is when $B=f_{s}/2,$ the Nyquist frequency.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] where $\mathrm {rect}$ is the rectangular function.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] which shows how the samples, $x(nT)$ , can be combined to reconstruct $x(t)$ .
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] Poisson shows that the Fourier series in **Eq.1** produces the periodic summation of $X(f)$ , regardless of $f_{s}$ and B .
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] Shannon, however, only derives the series coefficients for the case $f_{s}=2B$ .
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] is determined if its Fourier coefficients are determined.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] completely, since a function is determined if its spectrum is known.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] Shannon's proof of the theorem is complete at that point, but he goes on to discuss reconstruction via sinc functions, what we now call the Whittaker–Shannon interpolation formula as discussed above.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] He does not derive or prove the properties of the sinc function, as the Fourier pair relationship between the rect (the rectangular function) and sinc functions was well known by that time.
[src:waveform-audio/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] As in the other proof, the existence of the Fourier transform of the original signal is assumed, so the proof does not say whether the sampling theorem extends to bandlimited stationary random processes.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] Early electrical communications started to sample signals in order to multiplex samples from multiple telegraphy sources and to convey them over a single telegraph cable.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] Farmer conceived telegraph time-division multiplexing (TDM) as early as 1853.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] Miner, in 1903, used an electro-mechanical commutator for time-division multiplexing multiple telegraph signals; he also applied this technology to telephony.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] He obtained intelligible speech from channels sampled at a rate above 3500–4300 Hz; lower rates proved unsatisfactory.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] In 1920, the Bartlane cable picture transmission system used telegraph signaling of characters punched in paper tape to send samples of images quantized to 5 levels.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] Rainey of Western Electric patented a facsimile machine that transmitted its signal using 5-bit PCM, encoded by an opto-mechanical analog-to-digital converter.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] British engineer Alec Reeves, unaware of previous work, conceived the use of PCM for voice communication in 1937 while working for International Telephone and Telegraph in France.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] He described the theory and its advantages, but no practical application resulted.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] Reeves filed for a French patent in 1938, and his US patent was granted in 1943.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] By this time Reeves had started working at the Telecommunications Research Establishment.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] The first transmission of speech by digital techniques, the SIGSALY encryption equipment, conveyed high-level Allied communications during World War II.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] In 1949, for the Canadian Navy's DATAR system, Ferranti Canada built a working PCM radio system that was able to transmit digitized radar data over long distances.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] PCM in the late 1940s and early 1950s used a cathode-ray coding tube with a plate electrode having encoding perforations.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] As in an oscilloscope, the beam was swept horizontally at the sample rate while the vertical deflection was controlled by the input analog signal, causing the beam to pass through higher or lower portions of the perforated plate.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] The plate collected or passed the beam, producing current variations in binary code, one bit at a time.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] Rather than natural binary, the grid of Goodall's later tube was perforated to produce a glitch-free Gray code and produced all bits simultaneously by using a fan beam instead of a scanning beam.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] In the United States, the National Inventors Hall of Fame has honored Bernard M.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] Oliver and Claude Shannon as the inventors of PCM, as described in "Communication System Employing Pulse Code Modulation", U.S. patent 2,801,281 filed in 1946 and 1952, granted in 1956.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] Another patent by the same title was filed by John R.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] The three of them published "The Philosophy of PCM" in 1948.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] The T-carrier system, introduced in 1961, uses two twisted-pair transmission lines to carry 24 PCM telephone calls sampled at 8 kHz and 8-bit resolution.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] This development improved capacity and call quality compared to the previous frequency-division multiplexing schemes.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] In 1973, adaptive differential pulse-code modulation (ADPCM) was developed, by P.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] In 1967, the first PCM recorder was developed by NHK's research facilities in Japan.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] The 30 kHz 12-bit device used a compander (similar to DBX Noise Reduction) to extend the dynamic range, and stored the signals on a video tape recorder.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] In 1969, NHK expanded the system's capabilities to 2-channel stereo and 32 kHz 13-bit resolution.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] In January 1971, using NHK's PCM recording system, engineers at Denon recorded the first commercial digital recordings.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] In 1972, Denon unveiled the first 8-channel digital recorder, the DN-023R, which used a 4-head open reel broadcast video tape recorder to record in 47.25 kHz, 13-bit PCM audio.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] In 1977, Denon developed the portable PCM recording system, the DN-034R.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] In 1979, the first digital pop album, Bop till You Drop, was recorded.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] It was recorded in 50 kHz, 16-bit linear PCM using a 3M digital tape recorder.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] The compact disc (CD) brought PCM to consumer audio applications with its introduction in 1982.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] The CD uses a 44,100 Hz sampling frequency and 16-bit resolution and stores up to 80 minutes of stereo audio per disc.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] The rapid development and wide adoption of PCM digital telephony was enabled by metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) switched capacitor (SC) circuit technology, developed in the early 1970s.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] This led to the development of PCM codec-filter chips in the late 1970s.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] The silicon-gate CMOS (complementary MOS) PCM codec-filter chip, developed by David A.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] Black in 1980, has since been the industry standard for digital telephony.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] PCM is the method of encoding typically used for uncompressed digital audio.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] In the diagram, a sine wave (red curve) is sampled and quantized for PCM.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] The sine wave is sampled at regular intervals, shown as vertical lines.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] For each sample, one of the available values (on the y-axis) is chosen.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] The PCM process is commonly implemented on a single integrated circuit called an analog-to-digital converter (ADC).
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] This produces a fully discrete representation of the input signal (blue points) that can be easily encoded as digital data for storage or manipulation.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] Several PCM streams could also be multiplexed into a larger aggregate data stream, generally for transmission of multiple streams over a single physical link.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] One technique is called time-division multiplexing (TDM) and is widely used, notably in the modern public telephone system.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] The electronics involved in producing an accurate analog signal from the discrete data are similar to those used for generating the digital signal.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] These devices are digital-to-analog converters (DACs).
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] They produce a voltage or current (depending on type) that represents the value presented on their digital inputs.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] This output would then generally be filtered and amplified for use.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] To recover the original signal from the sampled data, a *demodulator* can apply the procedure of modulation in reverse.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] After each sampling period, the demodulator reads the next value and transitions the output signal to the new value.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] As a result of these transitions, the signal retains a significant amount of high-frequency energy due to imaging effects.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] To remove these undesirable frequencies, the demodulator passes the signal through a reconstruction filter that suppresses energy outside the expected frequency range (greater than the Nyquist frequency $f_{s}/2$ ).
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] Common sample depths for LPCM are 8, 16, 20 or 24 bits per sample.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] Support for multichannel audio depends on file format and relies on synchronization of multiple LPCM streams.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] While two channels (stereo) is the most common format, systems can support up to 8 audio channels (7.1 surround) or more.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] Common sampling frequencies are 48 kHz as used with DVD format videos, or 44.1 kHz as used in CDs.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] Sampling frequencies of 96 kHz or 192 kHz can be used on some equipment, but the benefits have been debated.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] The Nyquist–Shannon sampling theorem shows PCM devices can operate without introducing distortions within their designed frequency bands if they provide a sampling frequency at least twice that of the highest frequency contained in the input signal.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] For example, in telephony, the usable voice frequency band ranges from approximately 300 to 3400 Hz.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] For effective reconstruction of the voice signal, telephony applications therefore typically use an 8000 Hz sampling frequency which is more than twice the highest usable voice frequency.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] Some forms of PCM combine signal processing with coding.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] Older versions of these systems applied the processing in the analog domain as part of the analog-to-digital process; newer implementations do so in the digital domain.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] These simple techniques have been largely rendered obsolete by modern transform-based audio compression techniques, such as modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT) coding.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] In telephony, a standard audio signal for a single phone call is encoded as 8,000 samples per second, of 8 bits each, giving a 64 kbit/s digital signal known as DS0.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] The default signal compression encoding on a DS0 is either μ-law (mu-law) PCM (North America and Japan) or A-law PCM (Europe and most of the rest of the world).
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] These are logarithmic compression systems where a 12- or 13-bit linear PCM sample number is mapped into an 8-bit value.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] This system is described by international standard G.711.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] Where circuit costs are high and loss of voice quality is acceptable, it sometimes makes sense to compress the voice signal even further.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] An ADPCM algorithm is used to map a series of 8-bit μ-law or A-law PCM samples into a series of 4-bit ADPCM samples.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] In this way, the capacity of the line is doubled.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] The technique is detailed in the G.726 standard.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] Audio coding formats and audio codecs have been developed to achieve further compression.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] Some of these techniques have been standardized and patented.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] Advanced compression techniques, such as modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT) and linear predictive coding (LPC), are now widely used in mobile phones, voice over IP (VoIP) and streaming media.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] PCM can be either return-to-zero (RZ) or non-return-to-zero (NRZ).
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] For a NRZ system to be synchronized using in-band information, there must not be long sequences of identical symbols, such as ones or zeroes.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] For binary PCM systems, the density of 1-symbols is called *ones-density*.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] Ones-density is often controlled using precoding techniques such as run-length limited encoding, where the PCM code is expanded into a slightly longer code with a guaranteed bound on ones-density before modulation into the channel.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] In other cases, extra framing bits are added into the stream, which guarantees at least occasional symbol transitions.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] Another technique used to control ones-density is the use of a scrambler on the data, which will tend to turn the data stream into a stream that looks pseudo-random, but where the data can be recovered exactly by a complementary descrambler.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] In this case, long runs of zeroes or ones are still possible on the output but are considered unlikely enough to allow reliable synchronization.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] In other cases, the long term DC value of the modulated signal is important, as building up a DC bias will tend to move communications circuits out of their operating range.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] In this case, special measures are taken to keep a count of the cumulative DC bias and to modify the codes if necessary to make the DC bias always tend back to zero.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] Many of these codes are bipolar codes, where the pulses can be positive, negative or absent.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] In the typical alternate mark inversion code, non-zero pulses alternate between being positive and negative.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] These rules may be violated to generate special symbols used for framing or other special purposes.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] The word *pulse* in the term *pulse-code modulation* refers to the pulses to be found in the transmission line.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] This perhaps is a natural consequence of this technique having evolved alongside two analog methods, pulse-width modulation and pulse-position modulation, in which the information to be encoded is represented by discrete signal pulses of varying width or position, respectively.
[src:waveform-audio/pulse-code-modulation] In this respect, PCM bears little resemblance to these other forms of signal encoding, except that all can be used in time-division multiplexing, and the numbers of the PCM codes are represented as electrical pulses.
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] The Microsoft implementation is mostly known through the container formats AVI, ANI and WAV, which use RIFF as their basis.
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] RIFF was introduced in 1991 by Microsoft and IBM and used as the default format for Windows 3.1 multimedia files.
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] It is based on Interchange File Format introduced by Electronic Arts in 1985 on the Amiga.
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] IFF uses the big-endian convention of the Amiga's Motorola 68000 CPU, but in RIFF multi-byte integers are stored in the little-endian order of the x86 processors used in IBM PC compatibles.
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] A RIFX format, which is big-endian, was also introduced.
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] In 2010 Google introduced the WebP picture format, which uses RIFF as a container.
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] RIFF files consist entirely of "chunks".
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] The overall format is identical to IFF, except for the endianness as previously stated, and the different meaning of the chunk names.
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] Two chunk identifiers, "RIFF" and "LIST", introduce a chunk that can contain subchunks.
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] The file itself consists of one RIFF chunk, which then can contain further subchunks: hence, the first four bytes of a correctly formatted RIFF file will spell out "RIFF".
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] More information about the RIFF format can be found in the Interchange File Format article.
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] RF64 is a multichannel file format based on RIFF specification, developed by the European Broadcasting Union.
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] It is BWF-compatible and allows file sizes to exceed 4 gigabytes.
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] It does so by providing a "ds64" chunk with a 64-bit (8-byte) size.
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] The optional INFO chunk allows RIFF files to be "tagged" with information falling into a number of predefined categories, such as copyright ("ICOP"), comments ("ICMT"), artist ("IART"), in a standardised way.
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] These details can be read from a RIFF file even if the rest of the file format is unrecognized.
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] The standard also allows the use of user-defined fields.
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] Programmers intending to use non-standard fields should bear in mind that the same non-standard subchunk ID may be used by different applications in different (and potentially incompatible) ways.
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] In line with their policy of using .RIFF for all Windows 3.1 "multimedia" files, Microsoft introduced a new variant on the existing MIDI file format used for storing song information to be played on electronic musical instruments.
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] Microsoft's MIDI file format consisted of a standard MIDI file enclosed in a RIFF wrapper, and had the file extension .RMI.
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] Since the existing MIDI file format already supported embedded "tagging" information, this caused the disadvantage of having to deal with two file formats for the same type of information.
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] The MIDI Manufacturers Association have since embraced the RIFF-based MIDI file format, and used it as the basis of an "extended midifile" that also includes instrument data in "DLS" format, embedded within the same .RMI file.
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] For cataloguing purposes, the optimal position for the INFO chunk is near the beginning of the file.
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] However, since the INFO chunk is optional, it is often omitted from the detailed specifications of individual file formats, leading to some confusion over the correct position for this chunk within a file.
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] When dealing with large media files, the expansion or contraction of the INFO chunk during tag-editing can result in the following "data" section of the file having to be read and rewritten back to disk to accommodate the new header size.
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] Since media files can be gigabytes in size, this is a potentially disk-intensive process.
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] One workaround is to "pad out" the leading INFO chunk using dummy data (using a "dummy chunk" or "pad chunk") when the file is created.
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] Later editing can then expand or contract the "dummy" field to keep the total size of the file header constant: an intelligently written piece of software can then overwrite just the file header when tagging data is changed, without modifying or moving the main body of the file.
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] Some programs have tried to address the problem by placing the INFO chunk at the end of a media file, after the main body of the file.
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] This has resulted in two different conventions for chunk placement, with the attendant risk that some combinations of software can cause a file's INFO data to be ignored or permanently overwritten during editing.
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] More sophisticated programs will take into account the possibility of "unexpected" chunk placement in files and respond accordingly.
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] For instance, when the audio-editing program Audacity encounters a .WAV file with end-placed INFO data, it will correctly identify and read the data, but on saving, will relocate the INFO chunk back to the file header.
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] Although CorelDRAW 10 nominally uses a RIFF file structure, the program's initial release placed the INFO chunk at the end, so that any embedded preview bitmap would not be displayed under Windows' file manager by default.
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] A "patch" utility supplied with the program fixes this problem.
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] RIFF information tags are found in WAV audio and AVI video files.
[src:waveform-audio/resource-interchange-file-format] The field consists of two values (v[0] and v[1]) separated with a space (0x20).
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] In signal processing, **sampling** is the reduction of a continuous-time signal to a discrete-time signal.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] A common example is the conversion of a sound wave to a sequence of "samples".
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] A **sample** is a value of the signal at a point in time and/or space; this definition differs from the term's usage in statistics, which refers to a set of such values.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] A **sampler** is a subsystem or operation that extracts samples from a continuous signal.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] A theoretical **ideal sampler** produces samples equivalent to the instantaneous value of the continuous signal at the desired points.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] The original signal can be reconstructed from a sequence of samples, up to the Nyquist limit, by passing the sequence of samples through a reconstruction filter.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] Functions of space, time, or any other dimension can be sampled, and similarly in two or more dimensions.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] For functions that vary with time, let $s(t)$ be a continuous function (or "signal") to be sampled, and let sampling be performed by measuring the value of the continuous function every T seconds, which is called the **sampling interval** or **sampling period**.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] The **sampling frequency** or **sampling rate**, $f_{s}$ , is the average number of samples obtained in one second, thus $f_{s}=1/T$ , with the unit *samples per second*, sometimes referred to as hertz, for example 48 kHz is 48,000 *samples per second*.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] Reconstructing a continuous function from samples is done by interpolation algorithms.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] The Whittaker–Shannon interpolation formula is mathematically equivalent to an ideal low-pass filter whose input is a sequence of Dirac delta functions that are modulated (multiplied) by the sample values.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] When the time interval between adjacent samples is a constant $(T)$ , the sequence of delta functions is called a Dirac comb.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] Mathematically, the modulated Dirac comb is equivalent to the product of the comb function with $s(t)$ .
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] That mathematical abstraction is sometimes referred to as *impulse sampling*.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] Most sampled signals are not simply stored and reconstructed.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] The fidelity of a theoretical reconstruction is a common measure of the effectiveness of sampling.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] That fidelity is reduced when $s(t)$ contains frequency components whose cycle length (period) is less than 2 sample intervals (see *Aliasing*).
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] The corresponding frequency limit, in *cycles per second* (hertz), is $0.5$ cycle/sample × $f_{s}$ samples/second = $f_{s}/2$ , known as the Nyquist frequency of the sampler.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] Therefore, $s(t)$ is usually the output of a low-pass filter, functionally known as an *anti-aliasing filter*.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] Without an anti-aliasing filter, frequencies higher than the Nyquist frequency will influence the samples in a way that is misinterpreted by the interpolation process.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] In practice, the continuous signal is sampled using an analog-to-digital converter (ADC), a device with various physical limitations.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] This results in deviations from the theoretically perfect reconstruction, collectively referred to as distortion.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] Although the use of oversampling can completely eliminate aperture error and aliasing by shifting them out of the passband, this technique cannot be practically used above a few GHz, and may be prohibitively expensive at much lower frequencies.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] Furthermore, while oversampling can reduce quantization error and non-linearity, it cannot eliminate these entirely.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] Consequently, practical ADCs at audio frequencies typically do not exhibit aliasing or aperture error, and are not limited by quantization error.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] At RF and microwave frequencies, where oversampling is impractical and filters are expensive, aperture error, quantization error and aliasing can be significant limitations.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] Jitter, noise, and quantization are often analyzed by modeling them as random errors added to the sample values.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] Integration and zero-order hold effects can be analyzed as a form of low-pass filtering.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] The non-linearities of either ADC or DAC are analyzed by replacing the ideal linear function mapping with a proposed nonlinear function.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] Digital audio systems typically employ pulse-code modulation (PCM) to encode sound as a series of discrete samples of the electrical level of an analog audio signal.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] Analog signals are captured (encoded) as PCM samples in analog-to-digital conversion (ADC), and reproduced (decoded) using digital-to-analog conversion (DAC).
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] The encoding used for the storage and transmission of digitised sound data within the system may differ.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] When it is necessary to capture audio covering the entire 20–20,000 Hz range of human hearing such as when recording music or many types of acoustic events, audio waveforms are typically sampled at 44.1 kHz (CD), 48 kHz, 88.2 kHz, or 96 kHz.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] The approximately double-rate requirement is a consequence of the Nyquist theorem.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] Sampling rates higher than about 50 kHz to 60 kHz cannot supply more usable information for human listeners.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] Early professional audio equipment manufacturers chose sampling rates in the region of 40 to 50 kHz for this reason.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] Conversely, ultrasonic sounds may interact with and modulate the audible part of the frequency spectrum (intermodulation distortion), *degrading* the fidelity.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] One advantage of higher sampling rates is that they can relax the low-pass filter design requirements for ADCs and DACs, but with modern oversampling delta-sigma-converters, this advantage is less important.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] The Audio Engineering Society recommends 48 kHz sampling rate for most applications, but gives recognition to 44.1 kHz for CD and other consumer uses, 32 kHz for transmission-related applications, and 96 kHz for higher bandwidth or relaxed anti-aliasing filtering.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] Robert Stuart state that the ideal sampling rate would be about 60 kHz, but since this is not a standard frequency, recommend 88.2 or 96 kHz for recording purposes.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] Audio is typically recorded at 8-, 16-, and 24-bit depth; which yield a theoretical maximum signal-to-quantization-noise ratio (SQNR) for a pure sine wave of, approximately; 49.93 dB, 98.09 dB, and 122.17 dB.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] Thermal noise limits the true number of bits that can be used in quantization.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] Few analog systems have signal to noise ratios (SNR) exceeding 120 dB.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] However, digital signal processing operations can have very high dynamic range, consequently, it is common to perform mixing and mastering operations at 32-bit floating-point precision and then convert to 16- or 24-bit for distribution.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] Speech signals, i.e., signals intended to carry only human speech, can usually be sampled at a much lower rate.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] For most phonemes, almost all of the energy is contained in the 100 Hz – 4 kHz range, allowing a sampling rate of 8 kHz.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] This is the sampling rate used by nearly all telephony systems, which use the G.711 sampling and quantization specifications.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] Standard-definition television (SDTV) uses either 720 by 480 pixels (US NTSC 525-line) or 720 by 576 pixels (UK PAL 625-line) for the visible picture area.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] High-definition television (HDTV) uses 720p (progressive), 1080i (interlaced), and 1080p (progressive, also known as Full-HD).
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] In digital video, the temporal sampling rate is defined as the frame rate – or rather the field rate – rather than the notional pixel clock.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] The image sampling frequency is the repetition rate of the sensor integration period.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] Video digital-to-analog converters operate in the megahertz range (from ~3 MHz for low-quality composite video scalers in early game consoles, to 250 MHz or more for the highest-resolution VGA output).
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] When analog video is converted to digital video, a different sampling process occurs, this time at the pixel frequency, corresponding to a spatial sampling rate along scan lines.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] Spatial sampling in the other direction is determined by the spacing of scan lines in the raster.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] The sampling rates and resolutions in both spatial directions can be measured in units of lines per picture height.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] Spatial aliasing of high-frequency luma or chroma video components shows up as a moiré pattern.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] The process of volume rendering samples a 3D grid of voxels to produce 3D renderings of sliced (tomographic) data.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] The 3D grid is assumed to represent a continuous region of 3D space.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] Volume rendering is common in medical imaging, X-ray computed tomography (CT/CAT), magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), positron emission tomography (PET) are some examples.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] It is also used for seismic tomography and other applications.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] When a bandpass signal is sampled slower than its Nyquist rate, the samples are indistinguishable from samples of a low-frequency alias of the high-frequency signal.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] That is often done purposefully in such a way that the lowest-frequency alias satisfies the Nyquist criterion, because the bandpass signal is still uniquely represented and recoverable.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] Oversampling is used in most modern analog-to-digital converters to reduce the distortion introduced by practical digital-to-analog converters, such as a zero-order hold instead of idealizations like the Whittaker–Shannon interpolation formula.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] Although complex-valued samples can be obtained as described above, they are also created by manipulating samples of a real-valued waveform.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] For instance, the equivalent baseband waveform can be created without explicitly computing ${\hat {s}}(t)$ , by processing the product sequence, $\left[s(nT)\cdot e^{-i2\pi {\frac {B}{2}}Tn}\right]$ , through a digital low-pass filter whose cutoff frequency is $B/2$ .
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] Computing only every other sample of the output sequence reduces the sample rate commensurate with the reduced Nyquist rate.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] The result is half as many complex-valued samples as the original number of real samples.
[src:waveform-audio/sampling-signal-processing] No information is lost, and the original $s(t)$ waveform can be recovered, if necessary.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] WAV is an application of the Resource Interchange File Format (RIFF) bitstream format method for storing data in *chunks*, and thus is similar to the 8SVX and the Audio Interchange File Format (AIFF) format used on Amiga and Macintosh computers, respectively.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] The WAV file is an instance of a Resource Interchange File Format (RIFF) defined by IBM and Microsoft.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] The RIFF format acts as a *wrapper* for various audio coding formats.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] Though a WAV file can contain compressed audio, the most common WAV audio format is uncompressed audio in the linear pulse-code modulation (LPCM) format.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] LPCM is also the standard audio coding format for audio CDs, which store two-channel LPCM audio sampled at 44.1 kHz with 16 bits per sample.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] Since LPCM is uncompressed and retains all of the samples of an audio track, professional users or audio experts may use the WAV format with LPCM audio for maximum audio quality.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] WAV files can also be edited and manipulated with relative ease.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] On Microsoft Windows, the WAV format supports compressed audio using the Audio Compression Manager (ACM).
[src:waveform-audio/wav] Any ACM codec can be used to compress a WAV file.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] The user interface (UI) for ACM may be accessed through various programs that use it, including Sound Recorder in some versions of Windows.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] Beginning with Windows 2000, a `WAVE_FORMAT_EXTENSIBLE` header was defined, which specifies multiple audio channel data along with speaker positions, eliminates ambiguity regarding sample types and container sizes in the standard WAV format and supports defining custom extensions to the format.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] It has a specific container format (a *chunk*) with a header that includes a four-character tag (FourCC) and the size (number of bytes) of the chunk.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] The tag specifies how the data within the chunk should be interpreted, and there are several standard FourCC tags.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] Tags consisting of all capital letters are reserved tags.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] The outermost chunk of a RIFF file has a `RIFF` tag; the first four bytes of chunk data are an additional FourCC tag that specifies the form type and are followed by a sequence of subchunks.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] In the case of a WAV file, the additional tag is `WAVE`.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] The remainder of the RIFF data is a sequence of chunks describing the audio information.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] The advantage of a tagged file format is that the format can be extended later while maintaining backward compatibility.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] The rule for a RIFF (or WAV) reader is that it should ignore any tagged chunk that it does not recognize.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] The reader will not be able to use the new information, but the reader should not be confused.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] The specification for RIFF files includes the definition of an `INFO` chunk.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] The chunk may include information such as the title of the work, author, creation date, and copyright information.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] Although the `INFO` chunk was defined for RIFF in version 1.0, the chunk was not referenced in the formal specification of a WAV file.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] Many readers had trouble processing this.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] Consequently, the safest thing to do from an interchange standpoint was to omit the `INFO` chunk and other extensions and send a lowest-common-denominator file.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] There are other INFO chunk placement problems.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] RIFF files were expected to be used in international environments, so there is `CSET` chunk to specify the country code, language, dialect, and code page for the strings in a RIFF file.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] For example, specifying an appropriate `CSET` chunk should allow the strings in an `INFO` chunk (and other chunks throughout the RIFF file) to be interpreted as Cyrillic or Japanese characters.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] RIFF also defines a `JUNK` filler chunk whose contents are not processed.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] The chunk allows a chunk to be deleted by just changing its FourCC.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] The chunk could also be used to reserve some space for future edits so the file could be modified without being resized.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] A later definition of RIFF introduced a similar `PAD` chunk.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] The top-level RIFF form uses a `WAVE` tag.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] It is followed by a mandatory `<fmt-ck>` chunk that describes the format of the sample data that follows.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] This chunk includes information such as the sample encoding, number of bits per channel, number of channels, and sample rate.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] The WAV specification includes some optional features.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] The optional `<fact-ck>` chunk reports the number of samples for some compressed coding schemes.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] The `<cue-ck>` chunk identifies some significant sample numbers in the wave file.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] The `<playlist-ck>` chunk allows the samples to be played out of order or repeated rather than just from beginning to end.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] The associated data list (`<assoc-data-list>`) allows labels and notes to be attached to cue points; text annotation may be given for a group of samples (e.g., caption information).
[src:waveform-audio/wav] Finally, the mandatory `<wave-data>` chunk contains the actual samples in the format previously specified.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] Note that the WAV file definition does not show where an `INFO` chunk should be placed.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] It is also silent about the placement of a `CSET` chunk (which specifies the character set used).
[src:waveform-audio/wav] The RIFF specification attempts to be a formal specification, but its formalism lacks the precision seen in other tagged formats.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] For example, the RIFF specification does not clearly distinguish between a set of subchunks and an ordered sequence of subchunks.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] The RIFF form chunk suggests it should be a sequence container.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] The `LIST` chunk definition for `<wave-data>` does use the `LIST` chunk as a sequence container with good formal semantics.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] The WAV specification supports, and most WAV files use, a single contiguous array of audio samples.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] The specification also supports discrete blocks of samples and silence that are played in order.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] Apparently `<data-list>` (undefined) and `<wave-list>` (defined but not referenced) should be identical.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] Even with this resolved, the productions then allow a `<data-ck>` to contain a recursive `<wave-data>` (which implies data interpretation problems).
[src:waveform-audio/wav] WAV files can contain embedded IFF *lists*, which can contain several *sub-chunks*.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] This is an example of a WAV file header (44 bytes).
[src:waveform-audio/wav] Data is stored in little-endian byte order.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] As a derivative of RIFF, WAV files can be tagged with metadata in the INFO chunk.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] In addition, WAV files can embed any kind of metadata, including but not limited to Extensible Metadata Platform (XMP) data or ID3 tags in extra chunks.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] The RIFF specification requires that applications ignore chunks they do not recognize, and applications may not necessarily use this extra information.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] Uncompressed WAV files are large, so file sharing of WAV files over the Internet is uncommon except among video, music, and audio professionals.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] The high resolution of the format makes it suitable for retaining first generation archived files of high quality, for use on a system where disk space and network bandwidth are not constraints.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] In spite of their large size, uncompressed WAV files are used by most radio broadcasters, especially those that have adopted a tapeless system.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] The WAV format is limited to files that are less than 4 GiB, because of its use of a 32-bit unsigned integer to record the file size in the header.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] Although this is equivalent to about 6.8 hours of CD-quality audio at 44.1 kHz, 16-bit stereo, it is sometimes necessary to exceed this limit, especially when greater sampling rates, bit resolutions or channel count are required.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] The W64 format was therefore created for use in Sound Forge.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] Its 64-bit file size field in the header allows for much longer recording times.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] The RF64 format specified by the European Broadcasting Union has also been created to solve this problem.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] Since the sampling rate of a WAV file can vary from 1 Hz to 4.29 GHz, and the number of channels can be as high as 65535, WAV files have also been used for non-audio data.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] LTspice, for instance, can store multiple circuit trace waveforms in separate channels, at any appropriate sampling rate, with the full-scale range representing ±1 V or A rather than a sound pressure.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] Audio compact discs (CDs) do not use the WAV file format, instead using Red Book audio.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] The commonality is that audio CDs are encoded as uncompressed 16-bit 44.1 kHz stereo LPCM, which is one of the formats supported by WAV.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] Audio in WAV files can be encoded in a variety of audio coding formats, such as GSM or MP3, to reduce the file size.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] All WAV files, even those that use MP3 compression, use the `.wav` extension.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] This is a reference to compare the monophonic (not stereophonic) audio quality and compression bitrates of audio coding formats available for WAV files, including LPCM, ADPCM, Microsoft GSM 06.10, CELP, SBC, Truespeech and MPEG Layer-3.
[src:waveform-audio/wav] These are the default ACM codecs that come with Windows.
